The effect of the different pore sizes of sintered glass foams on the J-V behavior is shown in Fig.3a, using 62.0 wt% H2SO4 solution as electrolytes. Current density is negligible (<1 mA cm−2) at a voltage below 2.0 V due to the overpotential of the Pt mesh. As long as the capillary force still holds the electrolyte, the current density increases with the use of larger pored sintered glass foams, indicating higher conductivity and energy efficiency for overall water splitting due to better mobility of electrolyte in larger pores. At 3.0 V, a current density of 27.1 mA cm−2 was achieved using G3 sintered glass foam and it increased to 37.8 mA cm−2 using G1 sintered glass foam. Therefore, the G1 sintered glass foam was chosen for further study of the foam thickness, owning to the high electrical conductivity, low resistance, and high energy efficiency it brings to the DAE module.Fig. 3DAE module performance at 25 °C unless specified.
